            <entry xml:id="entry_kænt" xml:lang="os">
                <form type="lemma"><orth>kænt</orth></form>
                <sense xml:id="sense_d1258e69"><abv:tr xml:lang="ru">
                        <q>здание</q>
                    </abv:tr><abv:tr xml:lang="en">
                        <q>building</q>
                    </abv:tr></sense>
                <etym xml:lang="ru">Слово, если оно реально существовало, сближается с широко
                    распространенным восточноиранским названием ‘поселения’, ‘города’ %i*kantha%i,
                    %ikanta%i: <mentioned xml:id="mentioned_d1258e81" xml:lang="sog"><lang/>
                        <w>*kanθ-(knδh-, knt-)</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:id="mentioned_d1258e86" xml:lang="kho"><lang/>
                        <w>kanthā</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:id="mentioned_d1258e91" xml:lang="yai"><lang/>
                        <w>kant</w>
                        <gloss><q>город</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:id="mentioned_d1258e99" xml:lang="ps"><lang/>
                        <w>kandai</w>
                        <gloss><q>квартал</q></gloss></mentioned> и пр. Отложилось во множестве
                    названий населенных пунктов Средней Азии: %iТаш-кент%i, %iСамар-канд%i,
                    %iЯр-кенд%i, %iКо-канд%i, %iПенджи-кент%i, %iЧим-кент%i и др. От %ikan-%i
                    ‘копать’ (имелось в виду укрепленное, окруженное рвом и стеной
                            поселение).%n<bibl><author>Morgenstierne,</author><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_NTS"/><biblScope>XII 267</biblScope></bibl>. — <bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_Bailey._Asica"/><biblScope>22</biblScope></bibl>.</etym>
                <etym xml:lang="en">This word, if it actually existed, is close to a widespread East
                    Iranian name of a ‘settling’, ‘town’ %i*kantha%i, %ikanta%i: <mentioned xml:id="mentioned_d1258e120" xml:lang="sog"><lang/>
                        <w>*kanθ-(knδh-, knt-)</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:id="mentioned_d1258e125" xml:lang="kho"><lang/>
                        <w>kanthā</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:id="mentioned_d1258e130" xml:lang="yai"><lang/>
                        <w>kant</w>
                        <gloss><q>town</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:id="mentioned_d1258e138" xml:lang="ps"><lang/>
                        <w>kandai</w>
                        <gloss><q>block</q></gloss></mentioned> etc. It is found in many names of
                    East Asian settlements: %iTash-kent%i, %iSamar-kand%i, %iJar-kend%i,
                    %iKo-kand%i, %iPendzhi-kent%i, %iChim-kent%i etc. It is derived from %ikan-%i
                    ‘to dig’ (meaning a fortified settlement, encircled by a ditch and a
                            wall).%n<bibl><author>Morgenstierne,</author><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_NTS"/><biblScope>XII 267</biblScope></bibl>. — <bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_Bailey._Asica"/><biblScope>22</biblScope></bibl>.</etym>
            </entry>
